    From the manufacturer

    4K UHD resolution

    With 4K UHD resolution, you get stunning, life-like image quality and highly legible fonts thanks to 4x more pixels than a standard Full HD monitor. The large 31.5" screen provides more room to work so you can be more productive when reviewing lines of code or detailed images. And the VA panel offers wide 178 viewing angles for easy viewing in team huddles and when collaborating with colleagues.

    sRGB and 1 billion colors

    Brilliant Color with HDR10

    1 billion colors means 64x more colors than conventional monitors, enabling you to view and work with richer and smoother graduations in color. HDR10 reveal deeper blacks, brighter light areas, and a broader range of purer colors that are more true to life than ever before.

    Incredible Thunderbolt

    Thunderbolt 3 functionality means you can connect all your laptops, keyboards, displays, storage devices and power source with just one cable for higher productivity and efficient multitasking. TBT3 gives you amazing speed, transferring data at up to 40Gbps*. Equipped with two TBT3 ports and compatible with PC and Mac, the single cable can transmit a digital display signal, data (USB) and Ethernet (LAN) while simultaneously charging your device (up to 90W).

    *Specs are dependent on cable type.

    Ultra-Slim Bezels and Easy Dual UHD setup

    A 3-sided borderless frame gives the impression of one seamless display in a multi-screen setup. Daisy chaining lets you bring monitors together with just one single cable. With Thunderbolt 3, daisy-chain up to two 4K monitors or six total devices.

    Split Screen (PBP) and Picture in Picture (PIP)

    Connect up to two separate sources to the display and view them simultaneously with split-screen (PBP) technology. Perform work, like coding, in one window and see the results in a separate window. With the included Samsung software, you can make window management easy and maximize your efficiency.

    Adjustable Stand and VESA Compatible

    The ergonomic stand means you can quickly and easily adjust your monitors height and viewing angle to your eye level, offering a comfortable and customized view. Easily tilt, swivel and pivot by up to 90 to change the monitors perspective and meet your precise viewing needs. And with VESA mount compatibility, installation on a wall or separate mounting arm is easy.

    Easy on the Eyes

    Eye Saver Mode and Flicker Free technology help to reduce eye strain for a more comfortable work experience, even during long work hours. When Eye Saver Mode is active, blue light levels are lowered. And flicker-free technology eliminates flickering at all levels of brightness.

    Product Description

    The Samsung F32TU872VN features Thunderbolt 3 for blazingly fast data transfer speeds. Thunderbolt 3 also offers a single-cable solution which carries power and data, as well as an ultra-fast and secure wired Ethernet (LAN) connection, making for a clean, clutter-free workspace. And with 4K/UHD 3840 x 2160 resolution, you get four times the resolution of a standard 1080p monitor. See more lines of code, more spreadsheet columns, more web content, more documents at once. And with support for 1 billion colors, 99.9% sRGB and HDR10, every image and video will be rich, lifelike and full of razor-sharp detail.

        4.0 out of 5 stars The second monitor I received is now showing 5 dead pixels which were not there
        Reviewed in the United States on March 28, 2022
        Verified Purchase
        I've had this monitor for almost a week now and have to say that it is awesome! I am predominantly a Mac user (MacBook Pro 15" 2017) and occasionally use a PC. I mainly use this monitor to do work as a programmer/data scientist.

        I was a bit apprehensive about buying this monitor because of the previous reviews saying that the text renders in a pixelated or jagged way on the screen. I will agree that out of the box, text looks awful on this screen. I looked into this a bit more and took one Redditors suggestion to turn off the SAMSUNG MAGIC UPSCALE This did not resolve the issue. I kept playing around with the settings on the monitor and finally found a solution. Simply change the GAME MODE setting to "Always On". This immediately took care of the pixelated text problem. However, i will say that this screen is not a substitute for the Retina display on the Mac. The Mac screen is still far superior but if you're a programmer like me and need lots of screen space to do work this monitor is fantastic.

        Mike Bentley
        3.0 out of 5 stars A medium-quality, entirely adequate Thunderbolt Monitor
        Reviewed in the United States on December 16, 2020
        Verified Purchase
        I was looking for a 32 inch monitor with support for Thunderbolt 3. As most T3 monitors are very expensive, I decided to give this one a whirl. First, the T3 ports are tight enough to grip the Thunderbolt cable connectors without slipping out. Second, I have a couple other monitors on the work bench here (one being the built-in for a 2019 MacBook Pro 16); in order to get this monitor to be as bright as the other two I finally had to turn Game Mode to Always On, which disables a few of the other slide controls for the monitor. Otherwise the monitor just isn't bright enough for my needs, no matter what the other slide controls were set to. Third, the color quality is reasonable tho just a tetch washed out from the backlighting. Fourth, the T3 daisy-chaining feature works, I have a dual SSD drive with T2 ports at the end of the T3 chain, and the backups happen at night without issues, but about this I have a caveat: when you design a monitor that has Thunderbolt support, you have to consider what else user might hook up to it besides a second monitor, and allow user to turn off the display part without powering the whole Thunderbolt chain down with it. Right? Meanwhile I just set a blank screen saver to start after five minutes, causing the screens to go as black as possible -- but the backlights still glow.

        What else? I use the VESA mount for the monitor and have set aside the stand that comes with the monitor. The stand works fine, by the way.

        I did pick up a color calibrator and used it to adjust the display profile.

        Would I buy a second one? Yes, altho I have not yet done so. It is an adequate monitor for developing code (I am not developing color-accurate work product), the only thing that really bugged me is the brightness.

        Features I did not play with: PiP
        I do play Warcraft with this thing, seems to work fine at 60Hz.

        Addendum on 2021-05-24:
        I bought a second one of these as a refurb. Jury still out.
        One thing I belatedly noticed: the screen becomes much brighter (and the refresh rate jumps from 30Hz to 60Hz) when you uncheck High Dynamic Range under Apple macOS System Preferences>Displays while running Big Sur.

        Northumbrian
        4.0 out of 5 stars So far so good, has some quirks
        Reviewed in the United States on December 21, 2020
        Verified Purchase
        This is definitely a good "for the price" monitor, I use it for my recording studio and general internet with a top-of-the-line 2017 MacBook Pro. I thought this monitor was an especially good deal because the 2 TB3 ports and 2 USB ports spared me having to spend another $200 on a hub for all of the outboard gear I need to use with the MacBook. Interesting issue I had was a pretty bad hiss/crackle through the headphone port of my MacBook when it was plugged into the "laptop" Thunderbolt port on the back on the monitor. Looks like there has been a problem with headphone jacks/power supply interference with MacBooks for 10+ years, so this might not be the monitor's fault. I switched the laptop to the other Thunderbolt port and the noise went away. The MacBook is still charging via the other Thunderbolt port, so not sure what's going on with all that. The SSD I now have plugged into the "laptop" Thunderbolt port still works as expected and I don't notice anything odd like extra heat or anything. Fingers crossed I'm not setting myself up for a failure of some sort, I prefer my gear, especially brand new stuff, to be setup to spec, but again, for the price...

        Update 12/23/20: Theres a headphone jack on the back of the monitor (duh). I ran my audio line out of there and theres no interference with the MacBook Pro when its plugged into the 90w TB3 port on the monitor.
